The Spanish Anarchist Press in the 1920s and 1930s

The Spanish Anarchist Press in the 1920s and 1930s

1) Overview of the project

In this project, I aim to enrich existing literary and historical discussions of early twentieth-century anarchist production in Spain. I approach the investigation of this time period through the analysis of the cultural products that do not belong to the intellectual elites, focusing, instead, on a variety of popular sources, such as periodical journals and magazines. In particular, I am using text analysis to consider how theories of sexuality may or may not have influenced the anarchist movement.

For this reason, I have used a sample data of 30 articles published in the anarchist magazine Estudios (1928-1937) that were printed in Valencia, Spain. The questions I pose on this particular corpus are:

  • What topics were more frequently covered in these publications?
  • How (if at all) did anarchist magazines shape or contribute to the dissemination of contemporary sexological theories and how did they promote the sexual “education” of the masses during the early twentieth century?

2) Methodology

Ted Underwood explains that “topic modeling gives us a way to infer the latent structure behind a collection of documents” (http://tedunderwood.com/2012/04/07/topic-modeling-made-just-simple-enough/). Ultimately, I would like to process a larger corpus of texts from the early twentieth century in Spanish than the one I will initially be able to process. Topic modeling will enable me to compare anarchist and erotic magazines and, also, to address how topics covered in these publications may have changed over the period of time that I am discussing.

In this first approach to my analysis of a greater corpus, I have used text mining techniques to help me to understand and decipher the most highlighted features of this small corpus of anarchist’s articles. As Shlomo Argamon, et al. explain, “[t]ext mining techniques are commonly used to detect patterns in large numbers of documents. These tools are often used to classify documents based on a training sample and apply the resulting model to unseen data” (http://digitalhumanities.org/dhq/vol/3/2/000043/000043.html). For this first trial, I analyze a small corpus of articles from the anarchist magazine Estudios with the tool Voyant. While this is a very basic tool, it has provided me with new insights on the corpus of anarchism in relation to sexual education and how anarchist ideology deals with female and male sexuality. Lisa Marie Rhody discusses how feminist approaches in literary studies can also be applied to text analysis, claiming that “the language of feminist analysis, which challenges traditional modes of knowledge production, is well aligned with the practice of defamiliarizing a textual corpora in order to ask ‘new’ questions at different scales.” In this brief analysis, I will try to understand and summarize what the major trends are in this corpus.

3) Results and discussion

a) Wordcloud View
  • Most frequent words in the corpus: sexual (230); mujer (187); hombre (162); vida (157); sexo (113)

In this Word Cloud view, we can observed the most frequently used words in this corpus are: “hombre,” “mujer,” “vida,” “sexo,” and “sexual.” Other recurrent words include: “amor, nuestro, moral, social, educación, niño, espíritu, años, sexualidad, feminidad, matrimonio, madre…” From this first look, this corpus shows that importance is given to sexuality and education. The data raises the question of why anarchist magazines would deal with and problematize questions regarding the domestic life, household, marriage, education and sexuality of the society. For this reason, I am looking at the different conceptions and attributes given to sexuality in relation to men and women.

In particular, while the word “men” is important in this word cloud, this corpus of anarchist texts seems to be more interested in “women,” as the word is more frequently mentioned. Indeed, there seems to be an interest in women’s sexuality, and in words related to “feminidad,” “madres,” “educación,” “matrimonio,” and even “moral.” These words show that the anarchists are trying to speak for women and impose a particular vision of them, since the great majority of authors of these articles are men.

In addition, the distinctive words above—broken down by journal article—show that anarchist magazines are focused on sexual education in two ways: they write about how men and women should behave, and they link women to “procreation,” “motherhood,” “marriage,” and “hygiene.” But, at the same time, they seem to pay attention to the ways in which the perils of “homosexuality,” “deviation,” and “inversion,” are on the rise in the society.

b) Trends

In this section, I am interested in looking at the relative frequencies of words across the corpus. For that reason, I have selected particular words in order to compare them. These include “amor* , problem* , homosex* , perver* ,” to be compared to “ mujer* ” and “ hombre* ”. The discourses on science are related to the sexuality of women and men, but the interesting part is that women seem to be very closely related to homosexuality and love, whereas homosexuality in men is related to perversion.

  • Hombre

c) Terms and distributions

In this part, I am interested in looking at how words are connected with others, such as: hombre* , mujer* , amor* , inver* , homosex*.

  • Hombre*

  • Mujer*

A first look at these images shows that “hombre” occurs with “mujer”, “hombre/s” and “sexual”, while the most common phrases are: “hombre y mujer”, “hombres de ciencia” and “hombres de bien.” In the case of “women,” it not only refers to “man/men” but also to “feminidad” and “sexual,” and the common phrase “mujer de feminidad muy pura.” The first approximations show a controversial aspect, in fact: The anarchist movement is reproducing the bourgeois and capitalist models of gender and sexual hierachies. Wheras men are in charge of “science,” women are very much understood in an essentialist manner, given the phrase used for women.

  • Amor*

  • Invert*

  • Homosex*

Moving to the following words, the word amor* co-occurs with “mujer,” “pasión,” and “vida,” which seems to highlight that “amor” is linked to women. In the case of homosexuality, the visualizations shows that the most recurrent collocates are: “inversión” and “perversión,” but it is also linked to “amor.” In a sense, that the word homosexuality co-occurs with “amor” disrupts and shows how same-sex relationships are seen not only in a negative way, by associating them to perversity, but also, in a positive manner attaching them to the valued emotion of “love.” In addition, the relationship between words seems to be closer to “mujer, sexual, sexo, ciencia.” Furthermore, the word inver* (inversión, invertido/a) occurs often with “hombre,” “homosexualismo,” and “instinto.”

d) Conclusion(s)

With this project I want to contribute to the academic literary critical and historical discussions on early twentieth-century Spain by supplying the results of distant reading that DH tools afford. For example, text mining can potentially offer new ways of approaching my corpus of texts, since most critical analyses focus mostly on canonical literary works or work by analyzing in depth fewer texts.

From this my first text analysis experiment, I have gleaned a new perspective on how to trace social and political movements. It seems that Spanish anarchism influenced how knowledge about sexuality was disseminated to the majority of the population, which was not the educated or the elite. It seems that the sexual education that anarchist promoted is rooted in the differentiation of men and women, and determines that women are seen in terms of their reproductive capability. Hence, a preliminary conclusion may be that anarchist thought about sexuality is not very different from prevailing bourgeois and capitalist views, but it may be more more franc in its discussion of these topics. In this first approach, when homosexuality is linked to women, it is usually described as “love,” whereas if homosexuality refers to men, it is portrayed as a perversity.
